      <style>
        p { font-size: 24pt; }
        em { color: red; }
      </style>
      
      <p>I <em>love</em> CSS!</p>

<!--DOM = document objects module
    
    A Ruleset is made up of a Selector and Declaration Block:
    Selector = li, em or method (.something) etc - 
    Declaration block = { color: green; font-size: large } 
    Propery = color 
    Value = green

    CSS Selectors:
    CSS uses selectors to target and style specified elements or groups of elements in a an HTML document.
    Type = one type of HTML element, li, em etc - used to apply a style to a particular element like "h1" or "body"
    Class = HTML attribute that groups elements together (.blue) <p class="blue"> (example - entire paragraph)
    ID = an attribute that must be unique to a single element in order to identify it (example - single element)

    
    Type selector: applies to particular type of HTML element, i.e paragraph for instance 

    p {
       background-color: yellow;
    }

    or you can group elements together, like below:

    p, h1, h2 {
        background-color: yellow;
     }

     ID (#) selector applies styling to all elements matching the ID:

     The below code can be divided into two parts. 
     One part DEFINES the style and the other part APPLIES the style to an HTML element.

     DEFINES THE STYLE: 
     <style>
      #introduction {
        font-weight: bold;
       }
       </style>

       APPLIES THE STYLE:
       <p id="introduction">Welcome to my page ...</p>

      Class (.) selectors apply the SAME styling to all elements that match a specified class attribute: 

CLASS EXAMPLE
Step 1 - DEFINE THE STYLE
Step 2 - APPLY THE STYLE

<style>
li {
  font-size: 1.5em;
}
.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
  font-weight: bold;
  color: red;
}
.done {
  text-decoration: line-through;
}
</style>
<h1>To-do:</h1>
<ul id="to-do_list">
  <li class="done highlight">Buy milk
  <li>Buy eggs
  <li class="done">Buy flour
  <li class="done highlight">Make waffles
  <li>Do laundry
  <li class="highlight">Learn to code
  <li class="highlight">Build a robot
</ul>


Type selectors are the most general, and set the style to a particular type of HTML element. 
class selectors set the style for multiple HTML elements that have the same class. id selectors are the most specific, 
and set the style to one specific HTML element.

BOXES EXAMPLE 1

<style>
  .blue_box {
    border: 10px solid blue;
    padding: 0.5em;
    width: 150px;
    height: 100px;
  }
</style>

<div class="blue_box">Hooray, a box!</div>

BOXES EXAMPLE 2

<style>
  .blue_box {
  border: 10px solid blue;
  padding: 0.5em;
  margin: 0.5em;
  width: 150px;
  height: 100px;
  }
  .red_box {
  border: 10px solid red;
  padding: 0.5em;
  margin: 0.5em;
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  }
</style>

<div class="blue_box">Hooray, a box!</div>
<div class="red_box"></div>


-->
